<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,941,829,851]" box="[151,941,829,851]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<typeStatus box="[151,201,830,851]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Koch, 1841" authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1841" box="[294,656,829,851]" class="Arachnida" family="Analgidae" genus="Dermaleichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corvinus">
<emphasis box="[294,529,829,851]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Dermaleichus corvinus</emphasis>
Koch, 1841
</taxonomicName>
, by subsequent designation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,895,1352]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
To date, nineteen species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canestrini" authorityYear="1899" box="[465,606,897,920]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,606,897,920]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trouessartia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been known to be restricted to swallows and martins (
<taxonomicName box="[1269,1432,895,920]" class="Aves" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Passeriformes</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors" authorityYear="1825" box="[151,304,932,957]" class="Aves" family="Hirundinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Hirundinidae</taxonomicName>
). Diversity and host associations of this grouping of mites have been most extensively explored in the Old World, especially in Europe and Africa, where 18 species were recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Santana, F. J." box="[1030,1188,967,992]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="1 - 128" refId="ref23807" refString="Santana, F. J. (1976) A review of the genus Trouessartia (Analgoidea: Alloptidae). Journal of Medical Entomology, Supplement 1, 1 - 128. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jmedent / 13. Suppl 1.1" type="journal article" year="1976">Santana 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaud, J. &amp; Atyeo, W. T." box="[1200,1432,967,992]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="263 - 274" refId="ref22305" refString="Gaud, J. &amp; Atyeo, W. T. (1986) Les Trouessartia (Analgoidea, Trouessartiidae) parasites des hirondelles de 1 ' Ancien Monde. I. Le groupe appendiculata. Acarologia, 27, 263 - 274." type="journal article" year="1986">Gaud &amp; Atyeo 1986</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaud, J. &amp; Atyeo, W. T." box="[151,211,1004,1028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="367 - 379" refId="ref22349" refString="Gaud, J. &amp; Atyeo, W. T. (1987) Les Trouessartia (Analgoidea, Trouessartiidae) parasites des hirondelles de 1 ' Ancien Monde. II. Le groupe minutipes. Acarologia, 28, 367 - 379." type="journal article" year="1987">1987</bibRefCitation>
). Reports of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canestrini" authorityYear="1899" box="[368,508,1005,1028]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,508,1005,1028]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trouessartia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species occurring on swallows in the New World are rather scanty. In total, 7 species have been recorded so far from hirundinids in this part of the world and only one of them, 
<taxonomicName authority="Mironov and Overstreet, 2016" authorityName="Mironov and Overstreet" authorityYear="2016" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stelgidopteryx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trouessartia stelgidopteryx</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Mironov, S. V. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." box="[317,661,1076,1101]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="3 - 9" refId="ref23412" refString="Mironov, S. V. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2016) A new feather mite species of the genus Trouessartia Canestrini (Acariformes: Trouessartiidae) from the Northern rough-winged swallow Stelgidopteryx serripennis (Passeriformes: Hirundinidae) in Pennsylvania. Acarina, 24, 3 - 9. https: // doi. org / 10.21684 / 0132 - 8077 - 2016 - 24 - 2 - 3 - 9" type="journal article" year="2016">Mironov and Overstreet, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, is a New World endemic, while remaining species are distributed in both hemispheres (
<bibRefCitation author="Cerny, V." box="[362,498,1111,1136]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref20831" refString="Cerny, V. (1967) Catalogo de la fauna Cubana. XX. Lista de los acaros parasitos de aves reportadas de Cuba. Museo &quot; Felipe Poey &quot; de la Academia de Ciencias de Cuba, Trabajos de Divulgacion, 45, 1 - 23. [Unpublished]" type="journal article" year="1967">Černý 1967</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Forrester, D. J. &amp; Spalding, M. G." box="[510,813,1111,1136]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref21908" refString="Forrester, D. J. &amp; Spalding, M. G. (2003) Parasites and diseases of wild birds in Florida. University Press of Florida, Gainesville, 1132 pp." type="book" year="2003">Forrester &amp; Spalding 2003</bibRefCitation>
; Galloway 
<emphasis box="[940,988,1111,1136]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">et al</emphasis>
. 2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mironov, S. V. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." box="[1074,1392,1111,1136]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="3 - 9" refId="ref23412" refString="Mironov, S. V. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2016) A new feather mite species of the genus Trouessartia Canestrini (Acariformes: Trouessartiidae) from the Northern rough-winged swallow Stelgidopteryx serripennis (Passeriformes: Hirundinidae) in Pennsylvania. Acarina, 24, 3 - 9. https: // doi. org / 10.21684 / 0132 - 8077 - 2016 - 24 - 2 - 3 - 9" type="journal article" year="2016">Mironov &amp; Overstreet 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,895,1352]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canestrini" authorityYear="1899" box="[199,340,1149,1172]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,340,1149,1172]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trouessartia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species associated with hirundinids do not constitute a uniform morphological grouping. Most of previously known mites belong to two species groups, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Berlese" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[791,951,1183,1208]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appendiculata">
<emphasis box="[791,951,1183,1208]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">appendiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(8) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Gaud &amp; Petitot" authorityYear="1948" box="[1055,1164,1185,1208]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutipes">
<emphasis box="[1055,1164,1185,1208]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">minutipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(9); 
<taxonomicName authority="Gaud, 1957" authorityName="Gaud" authorityYear="1957" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crucifera">
<emphasis box="[1225,1358,1184,1208]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">T. crucifera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gaud, J." pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="105 - 136" refId="ref22226" refString="Gaud, J. (1957) Acariens plumicoles (Analgesoidea) parasites des oiseaux du Maroc. Bulletin de la Societe des Sciences Naturelles et Physiques du Maroc, 37, 105 - 136." type="journal article" year="1957">Gaud, 1957</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is a single representative of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gaud" authorityYear="1957" box="[568,671,1220,1244]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crucifera">
<emphasis box="[568,671,1220,1244]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">crucifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mironov and Overstreet" authorityYear="2016" box="[804,990,1220,1245]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stelgidopteryx">
<emphasis box="[804,990,1220,1245]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">T. stelgidopteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been assigned to any group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,895,1352]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
In the present work, we establish a new species group, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mironov and Overstreet" authorityYear="2016" box="[853,1012,1255,1280]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stelgidopteryx">
<emphasis box="[853,1012,1255,1280]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">stelgidopteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which includes 3 of 5 new species described herein, we provide uniform diagnoses for all four species groups and present a key to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canestrini" authorityYear="1899" box="[1295,1435,1293,1316]" class="Arachnida" family="Trouessartiidae" genus="Trouessartia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1435,1293,1316]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trouessartia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species presently recorded or expected on hirundinids in North America (
<collectingCountry box="[972,1058,1327,1352]" name="Canada" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Canada</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1112,1173,1328,1352]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">USA</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
